{
  "text": " There was something that someone said at an iftar that we just hosted at City Hall. The other night, which really stayed with me though, is how Ramadan is also a lesson in the shallowness of instant gratification. Of how you spend all day craving food and craving water and anything you could fill yourself with. And then as soon as you break your fast, just a few minutes into eating, you already feel full. And it's as if you didn't spend that whole day dreaming of that very moment. We call it the city that never sleeps, but the atmosphere of New York City changes all of the sudden when Ramadan comes. All I think about is peace and quietness. Many ask me what it means to be the first Muslim mayor of our city. And in that question there is an assumption that I am introducing our faith to the city as a whole. When in reality, our faith has been a part of this city for generations. The question of whether it's been seen is another matter entirely. But Muslims and New York City, they are intertwined. MARCOFORD",
